nper cent.\nMore Cuts Likely.\nWill New York again lower its rate\nfrom 3 1 /a to 3 per cent? Will this be\nfollowed by England and other na\ntions? It looks that way now. Some\neven believe that several central bank\nrates will get down as low as 2 per\ncent.\nNaturally, the average reader says:\n\"I am paying 6 per cent for my\nmoney\u2014who Is borrowing this money\nat 3 and 4 per cent?\u201d\nThe answer is that this interest is\nwhat banks pay for their rediscounts\u2014\nthat is, for the money which they\nborrow at wholesale from the central\nbanks of issue. Many of them borrow\nat 4 per cent and loan at 7 per cent.\nBut this spread is narrowing now.\nMany banks which were receiving 7\nand 8 per cent from their customers\nsix months ago are receiving 5 to SVa\nper cent today.\nCall money rates have been around 2\nper cent this week, whereas a year ago\nthey were 10 per cent.\nCommercial paper rates are now 4 to\n4'/a per cent, whereas they were from\ns!i to 6 per cent last year.\nRates on 60 to 90 day acceptances\nare now from 2* to 2Vi per cent, com\npared with S l /a per cent last year.\nNow, what do these cheaper rates\nsignify? Certainly one thing stands out\nin the picture: Bonds\u2014the seasoned\nhigh-grade bonds \u2014are going to have an\nactive support during the next few\nmonths.\nIt almost Invariably follows that bond\nprices rise as interest rates decline.\nMoney is Plentiful.\nThe Federal Reserve member banks\nhave more money idle now than they\nhave had for months. They are ex\npected to be heavy purchasers of invest\nment bonds during the next year. So\nwill the Federal Reserve Bank itself buy\nheavily for its investments account, as\nits rediscounts are lighter now than\nthey have been in years.\nIn the last statement which the Fed\neral Reserve Bank made this week bills\ndiscounted for member banks have\nfallen to the lowest level in 13 years\u2014\nsince 1917.\nLast week the total amount redis\ncounted in the 12 Federal Reserve Banks\nwas $266,000,000. This week it is $205,-\n634,000, hardly enough to pay expenses.\nThe week of July 10, 1929, was the\npeak period in the Federal Reserve for\nrediscounts in recent years. Then this\nitem rose to $1,153,000,000. This seems\na large Item, viewing it from today's\nfigure, but in the year 1920, the year of\nthe last big inflation, rediscounts\nreached the total of $2,800,000,000, or\nabout 14 times the total today.\nThe total gold holdings against Fed\neral Reserve note issues and demand\ndeposits combined have reached 82.5\nper cent, against 80.8 per cent last\nweek.\nThe Federal Reserve never was in a\nstronger technical position than it is\ntoday.\nMcGarrah Statement.\nThe recent statement of O. W. Mc-\nGarrah, former chairman of the Fed\neral Reserve Bank of New York and\nnow president of the new Bank for In\nternational Settlements, that the direc\ntor*: of the Federal Reserve Bank of\nNew York voted an increase in the re\ndiscount rate from 5 to 6 per cent for\na number of weeks, from February to\nMay of 1929, when the stock market\nwas s zzling, only to be checkmated by\nthe Federal Reserve Board, which re\nfused to sanction the increase, throws\nsome new and interesting light on Fed\neral Reserve policy.\nIf the New York Federal Reserve\nBank, in the center of stock market ac\ntivities, voted to increase the rediscount\nrate in order to hold down speculation\nin stocks, why did the Federal Reserve\nBoard prevent such action?\n(Copyright. i#so. by North American News\npaper Alliance.)\nBUSINESS OUTLOOK HELD\nFAVORABLE IN SOUTHEAST\nThe business outlook for the next\nthree months is viewed as satisfactory\nby all industries in the Southeast, ac\ncording to Southeast Shippers\u2019 Advisory\nBoard. A slight increase in total ship\nments over the same period of 1929 Is\npredicted.\nThe brick, clay And products indus\ntry reported conditions generally in line\nwith those of last year. The iron and\nsteel industry looks for a slight increase\nin 1930.\nA general improvement In demand\nfor textile goods is likely, and the move\nment of cotton from warehouses to\nmills should be about 30 per cent\nheavier than last year.\nInformation received from the ma\nchinery industry indicates very little\ndifference in the market this year as\ncompared with last\nThe coal and coke industry looks for\na 10 per cent decrease, due to the ad\nvent of natural gas In Mississippi, Ala\nbama and a portion of Georgia.\nTransamerica Corporation.\nNEW YORK. March 22 OP).\u2014The\nTransamerica Corporation, holding\ncompany for the Gianinni enterprises,\nhas purchased the Occidental Corpora\ntion. Occidental Life Insurance Co. and\nthe Occidental Investment Co. Assets\nof the three companies approximate\n$25,000,000.\nConstruction Awards.\nNEW YORK. Mart* 22 </P). \u2014Heavy\nconstruction and engineering contracts\nlet in the United States last week aggre\ngated $181,886,000, the largest weekly\ntotal since the beginning of the year.\nEngineering News-Record reports. This\nfigure compares with $77,883,000 in the r a\nprevious week, and with 835,923,000 In 1\nthe corresponding week last year.\nGat Sales Increase.\nNEW YORK, March 22 VP).\u2014 Sales\nof manufactured gas in January ln\ncerased 3 per cent in volume and ap\nproximately 2 per cent revenues over\nJanuary. 1929, the American Oas As\nsociation reports.\nFOREIGN EXCHANGES.\n(Quotations furnished by W. B. Hibba <fc Co.)\nNominal sold Selling checks\nb\u00bbta. M\n.ftp JBP\nBerlin, mark 33.33 c Sf.MVbo\nRome, lira 5 29c ~.33He\nZurich, franc 19 3c 19.37 c\nAthens, drachma 13c\nMadrid, Peseta 19.3 c 13 50c\nVienna, schlllin* 14.07 c\nBudapest, penro 17.49 c\nPrague. crown inom 3.964 c 3. 96 Ac\nWarsaw, sloty 11 320\ngg, crown^. j 6 6c 367^ jc","height":"25527","width":"19716"}}
